and you make that
genuine commitment,

00:47:08.660 --> 00:47:10.100
I think people
will be impressed.

00:47:10.100 --> 00:47:12.058
And I've seen companies
like Google do it well,

00:47:12.058 --> 00:47:14.909
and I've seen companies
like Google swing and miss.

00:47:14.909 --> 00:47:15.950
So I hope you do it well.

00:47:15.950 --> 00:47:16.783
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:47:19.422 --> 00:47:20.950
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:47:20.950 --> 00:47:23.230
I'd like to follow
up on the fact

00:47:23.230 --> 00:47:26.920
that you described we have those
wonderful workspaces at Google

00:47:26.920 --> 00:47:29.170
and Facebook and
that contributes

00:47:29.170 --> 00:47:31.600
to that social infrastructure.

00:47:31.600 --> 00:47:33.970
Those things are not easily
scalable and replicable

00:47:33.970 --> 00:47:36.000
because one, they
cost a lot of money,

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:37.330
but also they're not perfect.

00:47:37.330 --> 00:47:40.210
Even in a workplace like
those tech companies,

00:47:40.210 --> 00:47:42.070
yes, we run into each
other as employees,

00:47:42.070 --> 00:47:46.890
but there's a gap between us
and the people who maintains

00:47:46.890 --> 00:47:48.430
those spaces and serve us.

00:47:48.430 --> 00:47:51.740
And we don't feel like real
community in that sense.

00:47:51.740 --> 00:47:55.480
So the physical space is
not a miracle on its own.

00:47:55.480 --> 00:47:56.880
It's one ingredient.

00:47:56.880 --> 00:48:02.980
And [INAUDIBLE]---- do you
see that technology can help

00:48:02.980 --> 00:48:05.430
providing a social
infrastructure on it's own

00:48:05.430 --> 00:48:08.270
without having to
rebuild stuff around us?

00:48:08.270 --> 00:48:09.890
And, for example,
I've been living

00:48:09.890 --> 00:48:11.560
in this New York
building for 10 years

00:48:11.560 --> 00:48:13.300
and I hardly know my neighbors.

00:48:13.300 --> 00:48:15.040
We have doors which
are separating us.

00:48:15.040 --> 00:48:16.990
If we take down those
doors, most likely

00:48:16.990 --> 00:48:18.614
there's going to be
a better community.

00:48:18.614 --> 00:48:22.810
But using technology can do
something to bring us together

00:48:22.810 --> 00:48:23.980
in the physical world.

00:48:23.980 --> 00:48:25.450
ERIC KLINENBERG: Very much.

00:48:25.450 --> 00:48:26.980
Absolutely.

00:48:26.980 --> 00:48:30.504
So I wrote this book with
a comedian about dating,

00:48:30.504 --> 00:48:32.170
and we talked a lot
about online dating.

00:48:32.170 --> 00:48:36.610
And clearly it's much easier
to find dates with Tinder

00:48:36.610 --> 00:48:40.120
than it was before Tinder
existed or OKCupid or Bumble

00:48:40.120 --> 00:48:41.980
or whatever it is
that you're doing now.

00:48:41.980 --> 00:48:46.540
And still like some people
spend too much time online

00:48:46.540 --> 00:48:48.457
and not enough time
dating because it's easier

00:48:48.457 --> 00:48:50.706
just to be in the phone
swiping left and right than it

00:48:50.706 --> 00:48:52.000
is to actually do the date.

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:53.661
But do I think that
the internet can

00:48:53.661 --> 00:48:54.910
help to bring people together?

00:48:54.910 --> 00:48:55.510
Yes.

00:48:55.510 --> 00:48:57.635
Let me give you two examples
of things that I think

00:48:57.635 --> 00:48:59.550
are really awesome.

00:48:59.550 --> 00:49:01.600
For very local
neighborhood things,

00:49:01.600 --> 00:49:05.924
Next Door is a very smart--

00:49:05.924 --> 00:49:07.840
I don't know-- do I call
it an app or website?

00:49:07.840 --> 00:49:10.220
Well, I'm going
to call it an app.

00:49:10.220 --> 00:49:16.397
It's-- I like the way that it is
oriented towards helping people

00:49:16.397 --> 00:49:18.730
make connections with people
around them to solve common

00:49:18.730 --> 00:49:20.250
problems or to share.

00:49:20.250 --> 00:49:24.010
And it seems to me like
it's a very effective tool.

00:49:24.010 --> 00:49:26.590
My family and I moved
to Silicon Valley

00:49:26.590 --> 00:49:29.150
a few years ago for a year.

00:49:29.150 --> 00:49:31.720
And it was really striking
how much people relied on

00:49:31.720 --> 00:49:34.450
Next Door there because
the scale of the place

00:49:34.450 --> 00:49:35.620
made it work really well.

00:49:35.620 --> 00:49:40.090
Doesn't work too well on 15th
Street, but it could probably.

00:49:40.090 --> 00:49:42.070
It just be get swamped.

00:49:42.070 --> 00:49:44.560
The other thing is like last
year, very unfortunately,

00:49:44.560 --> 00:49:47.590
I had three very dear
friends get cancer.

00:49:47.590 --> 00:49:49.979
And have any of you used
this website Caring Bridge?

00:49:49.979 --> 00:49:51.520
Do you know what
Caring Bridge, which

00:49:51.520 --> 00:49:55.750
allows you to build a community
around someone's care?

00:49:55.750 --> 00:49:58.780
So someone you know
gets very sick.

00:49:58.780 --> 00:50:01.180
Someone else or
that person starts

00:50:01.180 --> 00:50:03.640
a caring bridge program
where the person can explain

00:50:03.640 --> 00:50:06.010
what's going on with them or
their primary caretaker can

00:50:06.010 --> 00:50:09.310
explain or anyone who's
authorized to post can post.

00:50:09.310 --> 00:50:10.980
You can use it to
organize who's going

00:50:10.980 --> 00:50:13.900
to deliver meals, who's
going to visit the hospital,

00:50:13.900 --> 00:50:15.700
how to support one another.

00:50:15.700 --> 00:50:21.040
And I can't tell you how
powerful this website was

00:50:21.040 --> 00:50:24.730
in allowing me to understand
what my friends were going

00:50:24.730 --> 00:50:28.247
through and figure out how to
be a better friend and better

00:50:28.247 --> 00:50:29.830
supporter, not just
to the sick person

00:50:29.830 --> 00:50:33.230
but also to the people who are
on the front lines of care,

00:50:33.230 --> 00:50:34.820
which can also be exhausting.

00:50:34.820 --> 00:50:37.597
And I thought that's
a genius technology.

00:50:37.597 --> 00:50:40.180
And I actually don't need to be
face to face with those people

00:50:40.180 --> 00:50:43.240
all the time, but the connection
through stories and sharing

00:50:43.240 --> 00:50:46.630
information in Caring
Bridge worked really well.

00:50:46.630 --> 00:50:48.190
Those for me like
work much better

00:50:48.190 --> 00:50:53.890
than Twitter or Instagram
or Facebook even or Google

00:50:53.890 --> 00:50:54.704
Hangouts.

00:50:54.704 --> 00:50:55.870
Do you guys still have that?

00:50:55.870 --> 00:50:57.160
I don't know.

00:50:57.160 --> 00:51:01.450
It just-- those technologies
don't work as well.

00:51:01.450 --> 00:51:04.570
So I think there are
cases in which not having

00:51:04.570 --> 00:51:07.540
the face-to-face thing
can do a lot of good.

00:51:07.540 --> 00:51:10.630
But for the most part, what
I look for from technology

00:51:10.630 --> 00:51:16.150
is something that's going to
make it easier and more likely

00:51:16.150 --> 00:51:18.830
that I will meet up with
someone face to face.

00:51:18.830 --> 00:51:22.540
And I think there's a
real value in recovering

00:51:22.540 --> 00:51:26.040
that kind of face-to-face
interpersonal experience.

00:51:26.040 --> 00:51:28.900
It tends to generate a
level of depth and meaning

00:51:28.900 --> 00:51:31.540
and significance that
makes us all feel

00:51:31.540 --> 00:51:33.580
more satisfied and more human.

00:51:33.580 --> 00:51:36.930
And when we spend too much
time with our machines,

00:51:36.930 --> 00:51:39.370
I think we tend to feel
alienated from ourselves.

00:51:39.370 --> 00:51:40.810
At least that's my experience.

00:51:40.810 --> 00:51:43.180
I don't know how you
guys experience it.

00:51:43.180 --> 00:51:46.120
But everybody I know is trying
to solve the problem of how

00:51:46.120 --> 00:51:49.780
to spend less time with
their machines and more time

00:51:49.780 --> 00:51:51.559
with other people.

00:51:51.559 --> 00:51:53.100
Yeah, there's a
question in the back.

00:52:00.570 --> 00:52:02.120
AUDIENCE: Hi, Eric.

00:52:02.120 --> 00:52:04.100
I'm curious to know
what do you think

00:52:04.100 --> 00:52:05.885
the role of religious
institutions

00:52:05.885 --> 00:52:09.630
are in the social
infrastructure.

00:52:09.630 --> 00:52:11.060
And then another
question related

00:52:11.060 --> 00:52:13.550
to that is do you think
there is a causal factor that

00:52:13.550 --> 00:52:15.710
is cause for the decline
in both the libraries

00:52:15.710 --> 00:52:18.297
and religious institutions?

00:52:18.297 --> 00:52:19.880
ERIC KLINENBERG: So
I do think there's

00:52:19.880 --> 00:52:21.410
a role for religious
organizations

00:52:21.410 --> 00:52:23.990
and for other
nonprofit organizations

00:52:23.990 --> 00:52:27.230
and for for-profit organizations
and social infrastructure.

00:52:27.230 --> 00:52:29.420
I think we have such
profound deficits

00:52:29.420 --> 00:52:34.970
in our social infrastructure,
and given the nature

00:52:34.970 --> 00:52:40.070
of inequality, I think our
only real hope for addressing

00:52:40.070 --> 00:52:41.990
the deficiencies in
social infrastructure

00:52:41.990 --> 00:52:44.090
is to do more public investment.

00:52:44.090 --> 00:52:48.440
But that said-- and it's a
realm of democratic politics

00:52:48.440 --> 00:52:52.670
where we have some collective
say as citizens and voters.

00:52:52.670 --> 00:52:56.180
But that said, how
could you go to England

00:52:56.180 --> 00:52:58.820
and not recognize
that the pub, which

00:52:58.820 --> 00:53:01.602
is a for-profit institution,
is a central part

00:53:01.602 --> 00:53:02.810
of the social infrastructure?

00:53:02.810 --> 00:53:05.101
Or how could you go to an
African-American neighborhood

00:53:05.101 --> 00:53:06.680
in Chicago where
I grew up and not

00:53:06.680 --> 00:53:11.460
see that the beauty salon or
the barbershop is a key place,

00:53:11.460 --> 00:53:15.880
and those are for-profit
institutions and the diner

00:53:15.880 --> 00:53:16.760
and things like that.

00:53:16.760 --> 00:53:19.390
Religious organizations,
classic social infrastructure.

00:53:19.390 --> 00:53:23.660
In fact the chapter in my book
that's about climate change

00:53:23.660 --> 00:53:27.170
as a problem of building a
collective to manage something

00:53:27.170 --> 00:53:30.920
collaboratively begins with the
story of an evangelical church

00:53:30.920 --> 00:53:33.320
in Houston that made a
principled commitment

00:53:33.320 --> 00:53:38.370
to be a multi-ethnic,
multiracial community.

00:53:38.370 --> 00:53:43.490
And because of its
strengths and deep ties

00:53:43.490 --> 00:53:46.130
was able to do tremendous work
in the immediate aftermath

00:53:46.130 --> 00:53:49.970
of Hurricane Harvey
1 and 1/2 years ago.

00:53:49.970 --> 00:53:51.710
And so I think
religious organizations

00:53:51.710 --> 00:53:53.690
can play a central role.

00:53:53.690 --> 00:53:56.150
Now the issue with
religious organizations

00:53:56.150 --> 00:53:58.070
and also with
private sector places

00:53:58.070 --> 00:54:01.190
is that they have the
capacity to get exclusive.

00:54:01.190 --> 00:54:04.490
Some cases their exclusive
by definition, and that

00:54:04.490 --> 00:54:06.840
means they might
not serve everyone.

00:54:06.840 --> 00:54:08.756
They might help only
members of a group.

00:54:08.756 --> 00:54:10.880
And in some cases, you
might have a religious group

00:54:10.880 --> 00:54:15.160
that says principally it
will help people in its group

00:54:15.160 --> 00:54:16.610
and exclude others.

00:54:16.610 --> 00:54:18.110
It turns out this
church in Houston

00:54:18.110 --> 00:54:20.497
did the opposite even during
this event, which is great.

00:54:20.497 --> 00:54:22.580
But they're very exclusive
religious organizations

00:54:22.580 --> 00:54:26.031
as we know of all varieties.

00:54:26.031 --> 00:54:27.530
And then you guys
all know the story

00:54:27.530 --> 00:54:30.160
of what happened in Starbucks in
Philadelphia this past summer.

00:54:30.160 --> 00:54:31.620
Do you remember that experience?

00:54:31.620 --> 00:54:33.830
A lot of people,
it was Starbucks

00:54:33.830 --> 00:54:37.640
is a like a third space.

00:54:37.640 --> 00:54:40.730
It's practically a
public space now.

00:54:40.730 --> 00:54:43.280
Except for that in
Philadelphia this past summer,

00:54:43.280 --> 00:54:48.539
these two African-American guys
went to meet a friend and--

00:54:48.539 --> 00:54:49.580
has ever happened to you?

00:54:49.580 --> 00:54:51.310
You go to a place
to meet a friend,

00:54:51.310 --> 00:54:52.310
and your friend is late.

00:54:52.310 --> 00:54:54.620
Has anyone ad that
experience ever?

00:54:54.620 --> 00:54:57.470
You're like, no, that's
never happened to me.

00:54:57.470 --> 00:55:00.080
So this-- their friend is
late, and they're waiting--

00:55:00.080 --> 00:55:02.520
I was just giving a talk at
a university a few weeks ago,

00:55:02.520 --> 00:55:05.347
and I asked the students if
they knew about the story--

00:55:05.347 --> 00:55:06.180
about what happened.

00:55:06.180 --> 00:55:08.388
And one student was like,
yeah, I know what happened.

00:55:08.388 --> 00:55:09.700
They kicked him out.

00:55:09.700 --> 00:55:12.241
And I thought to myself it would
have been such a great thing

00:55:12.241 --> 00:55:16.730
if they had just kicked
them out, if they had said,

00:55:16.730 --> 00:55:19.702
please, gentlemen,
we have a rule here

00:55:19.702 --> 00:55:22.160
that you have to order if you're
going to sit in Starbucks.

00:55:22.160 --> 00:55:25.340
So we invite you to come
and buy one of our coffees.

00:55:25.340 --> 00:55:28.600
Or worse would have been to say
I'm sorry you have to leave,

00:55:28.600 --> 00:55:30.540
but instead--

00:55:30.540 --> 00:55:32.150
I'm bringing you
with me everywhere

00:55:32.150 --> 00:55:35.650
I speak from now on--

00:55:35.650 --> 00:55:38.049
they said-- they
called the police.

00:55:38.049 --> 00:55:39.590
They called the
police on these guys.

00:55:39.590 --> 00:55:43.460
And it-- because it
was captured on video,

00:55:43.460 --> 00:55:46.970
it conveyed this fact that
all of us know and many of us

00:55:46.970 --> 00:55:52.040
experience which is that
private spaces, nonprofit

00:55:52.040 --> 00:55:56.240
or for profit, can
be inaccessible.

00:55:56.240 --> 00:56:02.060
And in Seward Park, it's if
you don't have a credit card,

00:56:02.060 --> 00:56:03.840
you can't go to
Grumpy's for coffee.

00:56:03.840 --> 00:56:08.930
But the truth is I could be a
70-year-old Chinese immigrant

00:56:08.930 --> 00:56:12.040
or native-born person who's
lived my life in Seward Park,

00:56:12.040 --> 00:56:15.230
and I know that Mission
Chinese is not for me.

00:56:15.230 --> 00:56:18.380
And then I'm not really
wanted in Mission Chinese.

00:56:18.380 --> 00:56:21.230
The buildings themselves,
the stores, the companies,

00:56:21.230 --> 00:56:25.594
they tell you who's welcome
and who's not welcome.

00:56:25.594 --> 00:56:26.510
It's very clear to us.

00:56:26.510 --> 00:56:27.968
We can all read
that kind of thing.

00:56:27.968 --> 00:56:31.490
So the trick for these
places is to make themselves

00:56:31.490 --> 00:56:35.560
as accessible as possible to
signal as much as possible

00:56:35.560 --> 00:56:36.560
that people are welcome.

00:56:36.560 --> 00:56:40.172
And not every place has
to be a democratic social

00:56:40.172 --> 00:56:41.630
infrastructure,
but if we want them

00:56:41.630 --> 00:56:43.860
to be like social
infrastructures,

00:56:43.860 --> 00:56:44.900
they have to do that.

00:56:44.900 --> 00:56:46.880
Is there like a
single line that's

00:56:46.880 --> 00:56:50.630
causing the decline in
religious membership

00:56:50.630 --> 00:56:52.670
and also the decline
in libraries?

00:56:52.670 --> 00:56:55.200
I think there are
different lines probably.

00:56:55.200 --> 00:56:58.070
And actually religious
institutions in the US

00:56:58.070 --> 00:56:59.690
are surprisingly robust.

00:56:59.690 --> 00:57:01.820
It's that I think
church participation is

00:57:01.820 --> 00:57:04.459
probably not what it
once was, but there's

00:57:04.459 --> 00:57:06.500
a tremendous number of
people in this country who

00:57:06.500 --> 00:57:08.900
keep on going to church.

00:57:08.900 --> 00:57:14.030
Libraries, I want you to know,
are buzzing with activity.

00:57:14.030 --> 00:57:16.610
The library usage
rates are soaring.

00:57:16.610 --> 00:57:18.980
And it might be the case
that people don't take out

00:57:18.980 --> 00:57:22.484
books as much, but
who other than you

00:57:22.484 --> 00:57:24.650
guys who are going to be
so involved reading my book

00:57:24.650 --> 00:57:26.233
and for the next two
weeks is actually

00:57:26.233 --> 00:57:27.280
reading a book right now?

00:57:27.280 --> 00:57:29.738
People-- we live in a different
cultural moment, and people

00:57:29.738 --> 00:57:32.330
are consuming information
in different ways.

00:57:32.330 --> 00:57:35.030
But people are using libraries
in all these amazing ways

00:57:35.030 --> 00:57:36.830
that I hadn't expected.

00:57:36.830 --> 00:57:40.400
So it remains a place where
early literacy education

00:57:40.400 --> 00:57:41.497
happens.

00:57:41.497 --> 00:57:43.080
And libraries are
teaching more people

00:57:43.080 --> 00:57:44.454
English as a second
language than

00:57:44.454 --> 00:57:46.390
any other public institution.

00:57:46.390 --> 00:57:48.300
They're doing
citizenship classes.

00:57:48.300 --> 00:57:53.300
They're providing connection and
companionship for older people.

00:57:53.300 --> 00:57:57.260
They're places where people
get free Wi-Fi access.

00:57:57.260 --> 00:57:59.330
And people learn how
to use computers.

00:57:59.330 --> 00:58:02.450
It's actually really interesting
to see how many people don't

00:58:02.450 --> 00:58:04.667
know how to do email
and go to a library

00:58:04.667 --> 00:58:06.500
and have the librarian
help them with email.

00:58:06.500 --> 00:58:08.500
But librarians are solving
all kinds of problems

00:58:08.500 --> 00:58:11.450
and enormous numbers of
people are using them in part

00:58:11.450 --> 00:58:14.660
because we haven't supported
other social infrastructures

00:58:14.660 --> 00:58:16.646
or invested enough in
other protected programs.

00:58:16.646 --> 00:58:18.770
And so if you spend time
in a neighborhood library,

00:58:18.770 --> 00:58:21.710
I think what you'll observe
is that libraries are overrun

00:58:21.710 --> 00:58:22.910
actually.

00:58:22.910 --> 00:58:25.190
And it's one reason
that I have been hoping

00:58:25.190 --> 00:58:29.712
that some great philanthropist
or political leader

00:58:29.712 --> 00:58:31.670
will make the kind of
commitment to the library

00:58:31.670 --> 00:58:34.797
that Carnegie made
100 years ago.

00:58:34.797 --> 00:58:36.380
Because we don't
have that vision yet.

00:58:36.380 --> 00:58:39.650
We have not had a compelling
leader make the case

00:58:39.650 --> 00:58:43.220
that the solution to our
crisis in civil society

00:58:43.220 --> 00:58:47.760
is to make a major
investment in shared spaces.

00:58:47.760 --> 00:58:50.810
And until that
happens, I think we're

00:58:50.810 --> 00:58:54.480
going to stay very much in
the crisis that we have now.

00:58:54.480 --> 00:58:56.300
Are we going to end
on that sad note?

00:58:56.300 --> 00:58:58.790
I want to end on a happier
note like free ice cream

00:58:58.790 --> 00:59:00.427
across the hall.

00:59:00.427 --> 00:59:01.760
JESSE HAINES: Thank you so much.

00:59:01.760 --> 00:59:02.885
ERIC KLINENBERG: Thank you.

00:59:02.885 --> 00:59:05.350
[APPLAUSE]

